Dutch

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

From tip +‎ -en.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /ˈtɪ.pə(n)/
  • Audio:(file)
  • Rhymes: -ɪpən

Verb

[edit]

tippen

  1. to tip (give a gratuity)
  2. to tip (give a hint)

Conjugation

[edit]

German

[edit]

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /ˈtɪpən/, [ˈtɪp(ə)n], [ˈtɪpm̩]
  • Audio (Germany (Berlin)):(file)
  • Audio (Germany (Berlin)):(file)
  • Hyphenation: tip‧pen

Etymology 1

[edit]

From Middle Low German tippen (“to touch lightly”), from Middle Low German tip (“tip, fingertip”), cognate with English tip, from Proto-Germanic *tuppijô, *tuppijǭ (“tip”), diminutive of *tuppaz (“top”).

Merged with Central and Low German tippen, dippen, düppen (“to dip, to dab, to tap”), from Proto-Germanic *dupjaną, cognate with tupfen and English dip. The sense “to type” is influenced by English type.

Verb

[edit]

tippen (weak, third-person singular present tippt, past tense tippte, past participle getippt, auxiliary haben)

  1. to tap, to strike lightly (often repeatedly)
  2. (ambitransitive) to type (on a typewriter or keyboard)

Derived terms

Related terms
[edit]
  • abtippen, antippen, eintippen

Etymology 2

[edit]

From Tipp, from English tip.

Verb

[edit]

tippen (weak, third-person singular present tippt, past tense tippte, past participle getippt, auxiliary haben)

  1. to make an informed guess
  2. to make a prediction (of a sport result, etc.)

Middle English

[edit]

Alternative forms

[edit]
  • tipen, tipe, type

Etymology

[edit]

Possibly from North Germanic/Scandinavian (compare Swedish tippa (“to topple over”)).

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /ˈtipən/

Verb

[edit]

tippen

  1. to fall, be overturned

Conjugation

[edit]
Conjugation of tippen (weak in -ed)
infinitive (to) tippen, tippe
present tense past tense
1st-person singular tippe tipped
2nd-person singular tippest tippedest
3rd-person singular tippeth tipped
subjunctive singular tippe
imperative singular —
plural1 tippen, tippe tippeden, tippede
imperative plural tippeth, tippe —
participles tippynge, tippende tipped, ytipped

1 Sometimes used as a formal 2nd-person singular.

Descendants

[edit]
  • English: tip
